\": \"C3H4N2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"1H-imidazole\",\n      \"common_name\": \"imidazole\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H4N2/c1-2-4-3-5-1/h1-3H,(H,4,5)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H4N4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2,3-diaminobut-2-enedinitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"DAMN\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H4N4/c5-1-3(7)4(8)2-6/h7-8H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H3N5\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"5-amino-1H-imidazole-4-carbonitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"AICN\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H5N3O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"5-amino-1H-imidazole-4-carboxamide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"AICA\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_018\",\n      \"formula\": \"CHNO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanamide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formamide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_019\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H5N3O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-formamido-2-aminoprop-2-enenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"N-formyldehydroalanine nitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_020\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H4N2O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"imidazole-4-carboxylic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"imidazole-4-carboxylic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite\", \"mackinawite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"348K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite/mackinawite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent-like conditions; H2-rich; maximum reported activity near 75C\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Fe-S surface mediated reduction of CO2 by H2 to one-carbon reduced product.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Included as a literature-supported hydrothermal entry point for reduced carbon flow into the network, not as a direct histidine step. Greigite-catalyzed CO2 reduction at alkaline vent conditions with maxima near 75C is supported by the vent-mineral literature summarized in the report, especially Lilova et al. (2020). This addresses Hydrothermal -> Surface interconnection without asserting unsupported direct histidine synthesis.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface reduction of formate to formaldehyde precursor pool\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"phosphate minerals\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-irradiated shallow pool; low-yield contextual feeder step\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photochemical reduction/activation of one-carbon species on oxide mineral surfaces to methanal-containing pool.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This connecting step is explicitly speculative and is included only to connect hydrothermal reduced carbon supply to the surface sugar network. The report emphasizes formaldehyde as a highly plausible prebiotic feedstock but does not specify a single exclusive terrestrial route; TiO2-assisted photochemistry is grounded in formamide and surface photochemical studies (Saladino et al., 2012; Saladino et al., 2015). This step is therefore a cautious connector rather than a validated histidine-specific transformation.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Formose entry: formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"phosphate minerals\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline shallow pool; borate assists sugar stabilization\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Carbon-carbon coupling within formose-like chemistry gives the two-carbon hydroxyaldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report identifies formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde as highly plausible prebiotic feedstocks and glycolaldehyde as the direct precursor to erythrose. Borate-assisted sugar stabilization follows Ricardo et al. (2004), while the general formose relevance is consistent with Decker et al. (1982) and the sugar-prebiotic context summarized in the report.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Aldol condensation of glycolaldehyde to erythrose\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"pH 8-9; borate stabilization; wet-dry concentration\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sequential aldol chemistry of glycolaldehyde furnishes the C4 aldose erythrose.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Yi et al. (2023) support erythrose formation from glycolaldehyde self-condensation near pH 8-9, while Ricardo et al. (2004) support borate stabilization of sugars. The report stresses that erythrose is plausible but unstable; this reaction therefore feeds the Shen bottleneck while preserving the documented fragility of the intermediate.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN plus ammonia to formamidine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"phosphate minerals\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-320K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"concentration in evaporitic pools; highly labile intermediate\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Ammonolysis/addition of ammonia to HCN-derived one-carbon nitrile chemistry gives amidine functionality.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Formamidine is required by the only demonstrated histidine synthesis of Shen et al. (1987, 1990). The report and V\u00e1zquez-Salazar et al. (2018) emphasize that formamidine is highly labile and its prebiotic accumulation is problematic; this reaction is therefore included as a low-plausibility but necessary feeder to the validated histidine pathway.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Shen-Miller-Oro imidazole ring formation to imidazole-4-acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"298K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none demonstrated; minerals included as concentrative/stabilizing agents\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"aqueous solution; formamidine approximately 0.3 M in the reported laboratory synthesis; Schiff base followed by Amadori rearrangement; yield about 1.6% from erythrose\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Erythrose condenses with formamidine to a Schiff base, then an Amadori rearrangement constructs the imidazole ring and yields imidazole-4-acetaldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the key literature-validated bottleneck. Shen et al. (1987) reported formation of imidazole-4-acetaldehyde from D-erythrose and formamidine via Schiff-base formation and Amadori rearrangement. V\u00e1zquez-Salazar et al. (2018) later criticized the prebiotic plausibility because erythrose is unstable and formamidine hydrolyzes rapidly, but this remains the only demonstrated route to the essential histidine precursor.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker addition on imidazole-4-acetaldehyde to histidine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"phosphate minerals\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none demonstrated; minerals included as concentrative surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"mildly basic aqueous solution; classical Strecker sequence\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aldehyde forms an imine with ammonia, cyanide adds to the iminium carbon, giving the alpha-aminonitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Shen et al. (1990) demonstrated conversion of imidazole-4-acetaldehyde through Strecker chemistry to histidine. The general Strecker mechanism under mild aqueous conditions is well established, and the report identifies this as stage 2 of the sole complete prebiotic route. Kitadai (2015) is relevant to the broader energetic favorability of amino acid formation, though not specific to histidine.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of histidine aminonitrile to histidine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"aqueous hydrolysis; overall histidine yield about 3.5% relative to erythrose in the Shen sequence\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nitrile hydrolysis via amide to carboxylic acid furnishes histidine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This completes the only demonstrated histidine synthesis reported by Shen et al. (1990), with analytical confirmation by HPLC and LC-MS/MS. The report emphasizes that this route is experimentally real but chemically fragile and low yielding.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Debus-Radziszewski imidazole synthesis\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"298K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none required in the primary report; minerals included as plausible surface concentrators\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"mild aqueous conditions; room temperature\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Condensation of glyoxal, formaldehyde, and ammonia through diimine intermediates gives imidazole.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Or\u00f3 et al. (1984) demonstrated mild aqueous Debus-Radziszewski imidazole formation; Kua et al. (2011) supported a 1,2-diimine intermediate computationally. This branch is included as literature-supported imidazole chemistry, but it is not claimed to be a demonstrated route to histidine, matching the report's caution.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN oligomerization to DAMN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"surface concentration on minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"HCN oligomerization in concentrated surface reservoirs\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Tetramerization of HCN yields diaminomaleonitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report identifies DAMN as a very plausible HCN tetramer and a central entry to aminoimidazole photochemistry. Ferris and Orgel (1966) and Ferris and Kuder (1970) provide the classical foundation for this chemistry.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"UV photoisomerization of DAMN to AICN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-320K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV irradiation at about 350 nm\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"strong surface UV flux under ozone-free atmosphere\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photochemical rearrangement of DAMN produces the aminoimidazole nitrile AICN.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ferris and Orgel (1966) and Ferris and Kuder (1970) showed near-quantitative photoisomerization of DAMN to AICN under UV. The report stresses this as strong evidence that imidazole rings form readily from HCN photochemistry, though not yet to histidine.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of AICN to AICA\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral-assisted hydrolysis/concentration\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"shallow aqueous surface environment\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nitrile hydrolysis converts AICN to carboxamide AICA.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report explicitly notes hydrolysis of AICN to AICA and highlights its importance as a purine-histidine biosynthetic link, while also noting that this does not provide a demonstrated prebiotic shortcut to histidine. Supported by Ferris and Kuder (1970) and the synthesis-context discussion in V\u00e1zquez-Salazar et al. (2018).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Canonical Shen pathway from formaldehyde-derived erythrose\",\n      \"description\": \"Reduced one-carbon feedstock enters surface sugar chemistry to make glycolaldehyde and erythrose, while HCN plus ammonia provides formamidine; erythrose and formamidine yield imidazole-4-acetaldehyde, which undergoes Strecker synthesis and hydrolysis to histidine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal-to-surface canonical pathway\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction supplies formate that is transferred to UV-exposed surface pools, then follows the Shen route to histidine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Erythrose-first convergence pathway\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface sugar chemistry first accumulates erythrose from formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde; separately generated formamidine then converges at the imidazole-4-acetaldehyde bottleneck en route to histidine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Formamidine-first convergence pathway\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN and ammonia generate the key amidine first; later erythrose supply from surface aldol chemistry converges to produce imidazole-4-acetaldehyde and finally histidine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct surface-only Shen sequence\",\n      \"description\": \"A purely surface network in evaporitic or shallow-pool settings carrying formaldehyde through glycolaldehyde and erythrose, then through the validated Shen-Strecker route to histidine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Imidazole contextual branch via Debus-Radziszewski chemistry\",\n      \"description\": \"Glyoxal, formaldehyde, and ammonia form unsubstituted imidazole under mild aqueous surface conditions. This pathway demonstrates facile imidazole formation but does not provide a validated route to histidine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN photochemical imidazole branch to DAMN\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN oligomerizes in surface reservoirs to DAMN, establishing a robust nitrogen-rich precursor branch relevant to imidazole chemistry but not directly to histidine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN photochemical branch to AICN\",\n      \"description\": \"DAMN undergoes UV photoisomerization at about 350 nm to AICN, showing high-efficiency aminoimidazole ring formation from simple HCN feedstock.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN photochemical branch to AICA\",\n      \"description\": \"AICN hydrolyzes to AICA, linking prebiotic aminoimidazole chemistry to purine-histidine biosynthetic logic without constituting a demonstrated prebiotic histidine route.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Bottleneck-focused histidine route through imidazole-4-acetaldehyde\",\n      \"description\": \"This target-focused pathway isolates the experimentally decisive late steps: once imidazole-4-acetaldehyde is present, Strecker synthesis and hydrolysis furnish histidine. It emphasizes the literature conclusion that the true challenge is precursor access, not the terminal conversion.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_011\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_010\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Histidine", "overall_strategy": "This network is centered on the only experimentally demonstrated complete prebiotic synthesis of histidine: erythrose + formamidine -> imidazole-4-acetaldehyde followed by Strecker synthesis and hydrolysis to histidine (Shen et al., 1987; Shen et al., 1990). To satisfy the requested multi-path topology without overstating evidence, the network distinguishes between true target-reaching routes and contextual feeder routes. Ten pathways are provided, but only those that pass through the imidazole-4-acetaldehyde bottleneck are histidine-producing; the others converge on validated or literature-relevant hubs such as erythrose, formamidine, imidazole, DAMN, AICN, and AICA that illuminate why histidine is chemically difficult. Hydrothermal chemistry is restricted to literature-supported supply of reduced carbon hubs such as formate and aldehyde precursors under Fe-S mineral catalysis, while surface chemistry handles HCN photochemistry, formose/aldol sugar generation, and the Shen ring-forming step. Biochemical chemistry is invoked only for the final assembly and acknowledgement that early biotic catalysis may have been required, consistent with the literature conclusion that histidine is likely late in geochemistry but early in biology.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "CH2O2", "iupac_name": "methanoic acid", "common_name": "formic acid/formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "methanal", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyethanal", "common_name": "glycolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,4H,2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "C4H8O4", "iupac_name": "2,3,4-trihydroxybutanal", "common_name": "erythrose", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H8O4/c5-1-2(6)3(7)4(8)9/h1-4,6-9H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "HCN", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "CH4N2", "iupac_name": "methanimidamide", "common_name": "formamidine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH4N2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H3,2,3)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C5H6N2O", "iupac_name": "2-(1H-imidazol-4-yl)ethanal", "common_name": "imidazole-4-acetaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H6N2O/c8-2-1-5-3-6-4-7-5/h2-4H,1H2,(H,6,7)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C6H7N3", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-(1H-imidazol-4-yl)propanenitrile", "common_name": "histidine aminonitrile", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C6H9N3O2", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-(1H-imidazol-4-yl)propanoic acid", "common_name": "histidine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C6H9N3O2/c7-5(6(10)11)1-4-2-8-3-9-4/h2-3,5H,1,7H2,(H,8,9)(H,10,11)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C2H2O2", "iupac_name": "ethanedial", "common_name": "glyoxal", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H2O2/c3-1-2-4/h1-2H", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C3H4N2", "iupac_name": "1H-imidazole", "common_name": "imidazole", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4N2/c1-2-4-3-5-1/h1-3H,(H,4,5)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C4H4N4", "iupac_name": "2,3-diaminobut-2-enedinitrile", "common_name": "DAMN", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H4N4/c5-1-3(7)4(8)2-6/h7-8H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C4H3N5", "iupac_name": "5-amino-1H-imidazole-4-carbonitrile", "common_name": "AICN", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "C4H5N3O", "iupac_name": "5-amino-1H-imidazole-4-carboxamide", "common_name": "AICA", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_018", "formula": "CHNO", "iupac_name": "methanamide", "common_name": "formamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_019", "formula": "C4H5N3O2", "iupac_name": "2-formamido-2-aminoprop-2-enenitrile", "common_name": "N-formyldehydroalanine nitrile", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_020", "formula": "C4H4N2O2", "iupac_name": "imidazole-4-carboxylic acid", "common_name": "imidazole-4-carboxylic acid", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_003"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite", "mackinawite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "348K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite/mackinawite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent-like conditions; H2-rich; maximum reported activity near 75C"}, "mechanism": "Fe-S surface mediated reduction of CO2 by H2 to one-carbon reduced product.", "reasoning": "Included as a literature-supported hydrothermal entry point for reduced carbon flow into the network, not as a direct histidine step. Greigite-catalyzed CO2 reduction at alkaline vent conditions with maxima near 75C is supported by the vent-mineral literature summarized in the report, especially Lilova et al. (2020). This addresses Hydrothermal -> Surface interconnection without asserting unsupported direct histidine synthesis."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Surface reduction of formate to formaldehyde precursor pool", "inputs": ["mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "phosphate minerals"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-irradiated shallow pool; low-yield contextual feeder step"}, "mechanism": "Photochemical reduction/activation of one-carbon species on oxide mineral surfaces to methanal-containing pool.", "reasoning": "This connecting step is explicitly speculative and is included only to connect hydrothermal reduced carbon supply to the surface sugar network. The report emphasizes formaldehyde as a highly plausible prebiotic feedstock but does not specify a single exclusive terrestrial route; TiO2-assisted photochemistry is grounded in formamide and surface photochemical studies (Saladino et al., 2012; Saladino et al., 2015). This step is therefore a cautious connector rather than a validated histidine-specific transformation."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Formose entry: formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_005"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "phosphate minerals"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline shallow pool; borate assists sugar stabilization"}, "mechanism": "Carbon-carbon coupling within formose-like chemistry gives the two-carbon hydroxyaldehyde.", "reasoning": "The report identifies formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde as highly plausible prebiotic feedstocks and glycolaldehyde as the direct precursor to erythrose. Borate-assisted sugar stabilization follows Ricardo et al. (2004), while the general formose relevance is consistent with Decker et al. (1982) and the sugar-prebiotic context summarized in the report."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Aldol condensation of glycolaldehyde to erythrose", "inputs": ["mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH 8-9; borate stabilization; wet-dry concentration"}, "mechanism": "Sequential aldol chemistry of glycolaldehyde furnishes the C4 aldose erythrose.", "reasoning": "Yi et al. (2023) support erythrose formation from glycolaldehyde self-condensation near pH 8-9, while Ricardo et al. (2004) support borate stabilization of sugars. The report stresses that erythrose is plausible but unstable; this reaction therefore feeds the Shen bottleneck while preserving the documented fragility of the intermediate."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "HCN plus ammonia to formamidine", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "phosphate minerals"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-320K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "concentration in evaporitic pools; highly labile intermediate"}, "mechanism": "Ammonolysis/addition of ammonia to HCN-derived one-carbon nitrile chemistry gives amidine functionality.", "reasoning": "Formamidine is required by the only demonstrated histidine synthesis of Shen et al. (1987, 1990). The report and V\u00e1zquez-Salazar et al. (2018) emphasize that formamidine is highly labile and its prebiotic accumulation is problematic; this reaction is therefore included as a low-plausibility but necessary feeder to the validated histidine pathway."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Shen-Miller-Oro imidazole ring formation to imidazole-4-acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "298K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "none demonstrated; minerals included as concentrative/stabilizing agents", "aqueous": "true", "other": "aqueous solution; formamidine approximately 0.3 M in the reported laboratory synthesis; Schiff base followed by Amadori rearrangement; yield about 1.6% from erythrose"}, "mechanism": "Erythrose condenses with formamidine to a Schiff base, then an Amadori rearrangement constructs the imidazole ring and yields imidazole-4-acetaldehyde.", "reasoning": "This is the key literature-validated bottleneck. Shen et al. (1987) reported formation of imidazole-4-acetaldehyde from D-erythrose and formamidine via Schiff-base formation and Amadori rearrangement. V\u00e1zquez-Salazar et al. (2018) later criticized the prebiotic plausibility because erythrose is