(2004), and the use of glycolaldehyde as a gateway to erythrose is consistent with the report summary and Yi et al. (2023).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Aldol/formose progression to erythrose\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite), montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"pH 8-9; wet-dry concentration; erythrose is minor and unstable\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"C2-C1 aldol/formose chemistry generates the C4 aldose erythrose, with borate helping stabilize otherwise labile sugar products.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Erythrose is the required sugar precursor in the sole demonstrated histidine synthesis. The report states erythrose is a minor unstable formose product (Decker et al., 1982) but can form from glycolaldehyde self-condensation at pH 8-9 (Yi et al., 2023), with borate potentially stabilizing pentose/tetrose-like sugars (Ricardo et al., 2004). This reaction directly supports the Shen et al. (1987, 1990) bottleneck.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN generation and accumulation in surface settings\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile), sulfide minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-exposed anoxic pools; represented as feedstock accumulation rather than a single experimentally unique route\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Surface photochemical nitrogen-carbon chemistry accumulates hydrogen cyanide, which then serves as the central nitrile feedstock for Strecker and oligomerization reactions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report treats HCN as a central and highly plausible prebiotic feedstock underpinning both formamidine formation and DAMN/AICN chemistry. This step is included as a necessary feeder and is not claimed as a histidine-specific demonstrated transformation. Its role is to supply the literature-established downstream HCN chemistry of Ferris & Orgel (1966), Ferris & Kuder (1970), Shen et al. (1987, 1990), and Green et al. (2023).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Formamidine formation from HCN and ammonia\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite (clay)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"concentrating pools; formamidine is highly labile in water\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"HCN and ammonia generate amidine functionality represented here as formamidine, the key but prebiotically problematic reagent in the Shen route.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The deep report explicitly identifies formamidine as deriving from HCN + NH3 but as extremely labile and prebiotically problematic, following the critique of V\u00e1zquez-Salazar et al. (2018). This node is essential because Shen et al. (1987, 1990) require formamidine at 0.3 M for the only successful histidine synthesis.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Shen-Miller-Oro imidazole-4-acetaldehyde formation from erythrose and formamidine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"298-310K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none demonstrated in the original work; minerals here act as concentrative/stabilizing agents\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"aqueous solution; formamidine about 0.3 M; Schiff base formation followed by Amadori rearrangement; reported 1.6% yield based on erythrose\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Erythrose condenses with formamidine to form a Schiff base, then undergoes an Amadori-like rearrangement that constructs the imidazole ring and yields imidazole-4-acetaldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the critical literature-established bottleneck and the only demonstrated prebiotic route to the direct histidine precursor. The mechanism and yield follow Shen et al. (1987) and Shen et al. (1990). The report emphasizes that this step is chemically remarkable but prebiotically weak because erythrose is minor/unstable and formamidine is hydrolytically labile (V\u00e1zquez-Salazar et al., 2018).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker conversion of imidazole-4-acetaldehyde to histidine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite (clay)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"mildly basic aqueous Strecker conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The aldehyde forms an imine with ammonia, cyanide adds to give the alpha-aminonitrile precursor to histidine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the classical Strecker stage of the Shen-Miller-Or\u00f3 route. The report states that imidazole-4-acetaldehyde reacts with HCN and NH3 to give the alpha-aminonitrile, which on hydrolysis yields histidine; Shen et al. (1990) confirmed the overall sequence by HPLC and MS methods.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of histidine aminonitrile to histidine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"aqueous hydrolysis during prolonged standing/heating; overall histidine yield reported 3.5% relative to erythrose\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nitrile hydrolysis converts the aminonitrile into the amino acid carboxylate, completing histidine formation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This completes the only demonstrated prebiotic histidine synthesis of Shen et al. (1990). Placement in the Biochemical category reflects the network framework's final assembly layer, not a claim of enzymatic requirement. The deep report notes that once imidazole-4-acetaldehyde exists, Strecker elaboration is comparatively straightforward.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Debus-Radziszewski imidazole synthesis\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"298K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none required in the original mild aqueous reaction; minerals here provide concentration/adsorption\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"mild aqueous conditions; room temperature\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glyoxal, formaldehyde, and ammonia condense through diimine-type intermediates to form imidazole.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Or\u00f3 et al. (1984) demonstrated prebiotic imidazole formation by the Debus-Radziszewski reaction under mild aqueous conditions, and Kua et al. (2011) supported a 1,2-diimine mechanism computationally. The deep report explicitly states this route forms imidazole efficiently but does not provide a demonstrated path onward to histidine.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN tetramerization to diaminomaleonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"surface concentration on sulfide/mineral substrates\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"HCN oligomerization in anoxic surface pools\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Hydrogen cyanide oligomerizes to its tetramer diaminomaleonitrile under concentrated prebiotic conditions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The deep report identifies DAMN as a very plausible HCN oligomer and a key precursor to aminoimidazole photochemistry. This branch is supported by Ferris & Orgel (1966) and Ferris & Kuder (1970) as the entry to AICN/AICA chemistry, but it is not a demonstrated histidine-producing route.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"UV photoisomerization of DAMN to AICN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-320K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV light around 350 nm\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"near-quantitative photoisomerization under strong surface UV\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV irradiation drives rearrangement/cyclization of DAMN to the aminoimidazole nitrile AICN.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ferris & Orgel (1966) and Ferris & Kuder (1970) showed that HCN oligomer photochemistry produces 5-aminoimidazole-4-carbonitrile under UV irradiation. The report emphasizes that this is strong evidence for facile prebiotic imidazole-ring construction, though not for histidine itself.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of AICN to AICA\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral-assisted hydrolysis/concentration\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"aqueous hydrolysis in surface pools\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nitrile hydrolysis converts AICN to the corresponding carboxamide AICA.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report identifies AICN hydrolysis to AICA as a known extension of HCN photochemistry and notes AICA/AICAR as evolutionarily significant links between purine and histidine metabolism. This chemistry is contextual rather than target-achieving for histidine (Ferris & Kuder, 1970; V\u00e1zquez-Salazar et al., 2018).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"FoDHA-CN cyanide cascade to an imidazole derivative\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_019\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_020\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"298K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"cyanide in formamide-rich alkaline medium\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"pH 9.2; reported 63% yield of an imidazole derivative\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Cyanide addition initiates a cascade that forms three new C-N bonds and constructs an imidazole derivative from N-formyldehydroalanine nitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Green, Xu, & Sutherland (2023) reported this high-yielding imidazole-forming cascade. The deep report highlights it as a promising modern advance but explicitly states that extension to histidine or imidazole-4-acetaldehyde has not been demonstrated. It is therefore included as a connected comparative branch only.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Histidine peptide bond formation to His-His dipeptide on mineral interfaces\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_021\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"330-360K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry cycling on mineral surfaces; mineral-assisted self-assembly and peptide bond formation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Concentrated histidine on mineral interfaces self-assembles and dehydrates to form peptide bonds, giving small histidyl peptides.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Madrigal-Trejo et al. (2021) showed that histidine self-assembles and forms peptide bonds on antigorite, pyrite, and aragonite surfaces, with enhanced thermal stability. White & Erickson (1981) further showed catalytic relevance of His-His in prebiotic peptide chemistry. This reaction is downstream of target formation and illustrates why even scarce histidine could have been selectively valuable.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Validated Shen-Miller-Oro histidine pathway\",\n      \"description\": \"The sole experimentally demonstrated complete prebiotic route to histidine: erythrose and formamidine give imidazole-4-acetaldehyde by Schiff-base formation and Amadori rearrangement, followed by Strecker conversion and hydrolysis to histidine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal-to-surface carbon feed into validated histidine route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction supplies reduced carbon that is transferred to surface formaldehyde and then into the erythrose-dependent Shen pathway.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface sugar-supply route to erythrose bottleneck\",\n      \"description\": \"Formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde in borate-stabilized surface chemistry converge on erythrose, the sugar precursor required for the only known histidine synthesis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN-to-formamidine feeder route into validated histidine synthesis\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface HCN accumulation and amidine formation generate the key but prebiotically problematic formamidine reagent needed for the Shen route.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Bottleneck-only completion from imidazole-4-acetaldehyde\",\n      \"description\": \"If the crucial intermediate imidazole-4-acetaldehyde is granted, Strecker chemistry and hydrolysis complete histidine formation efficiently relative to the difficulty of making the aldehyde.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Debus-Radziszewski imidazole context branch\",\n      \"description\": \"A literature-supported alternative route to the imidazole ring from glyoxal, formaldehyde, and ammonia. It demonstrates easy imidazole formation but does not provide a validated path to histidine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN oligomerization to DAMN context branch\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN tetramerization yields DAMN, a robust feeder into aminoimidazole photochemistry and a key comparison branch showing that HCN readily builds heterocycles even though histidine remains inaccessible.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"DAMN photochemistry to AICN branch\",\n      \"description\": \"UV-driven conversion of DAMN to AICN shows near-quantitative imidazole-ring assembly from HCN oligomers under early Earth surface UV conditions.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"AICN to AICA purine-histidine evolutionary context branch\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrolysis of AICN to AICA links prebiotic aminoimidazole chemistry to purine intermediates and the modern metabolic intersection with histidine biosynthesis, but not to a demonstrated abiotic histidine route.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Sutherland FoDHA-CN imidazole cascade context branch\",\n      \"description\": \"A high-yield modern prebiotic imidazole-forming cascade from N-formyldehydroalanine nitrile and cyanide. It is included as the most promising alternative imidazole chemistry, though no extension to histidine has been demonstrated.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_020\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_009\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Histidine", "overall_strategy": "This network is centered on the literature-established conclusion that histidine has only one experimentally demonstrated complete prebiotic synthesis: the Shen-Miller-Or\u00f3 route from erythrose and formamidine to imidazole-4-acetaldehyde, followed by Strecker conversion and hydrolysis to histidine. Accordingly, the target-reaching chemistry in this network converges on the bottleneck intermediate imidazole-4-acetaldehyde. Additional branches are included only as literature-grounded feeder, contextual, or comparative routes that connect hydrothermal carbon fixation, surface HCN/sugar/imidazole chemistry, and biochemical concentration/polymerization. The 10 pathways therefore include one validated target-achieving route and nine connected feeder or context pathways that either supply required precursors, demonstrate alternative imidazole formation without target completion, or show downstream use/stabilization of histidine once formed. This design follows the research finding that histidine is likely a transition-point molecule between geochemistry and early biochemistry rather than a robustly available abiotic product.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "CH2O2", "iupac_name": "methanoic acid", "common_name": "formic acid/formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "methanal", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyethanal", "common_name": "glycolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,3H,2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "C4H8O4", "iupac_name": "2,3,4-trihydroxybutanal", "common_name": "erythrose", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H8O4/c5-1-2(6)3(7)4(8)9/h1-4,6-9H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "CHN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "HCN", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "CH4N2", "iupac_name": "methanimidamide", "common_name": "formamidine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH4N2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H3,2,3)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C5H6N2O", "iupac_name": "2-(1H-imidazol-4-yl)ethanal", "common_name": "imidazole-4-acetaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H6N2O/c8-2-1-5-3-6-4-7-5/h2-4H,1H2,(H,6,7)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C6H8N4", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-(1H-imidazol-4-yl)propanenitrile", "common_name": "histidine aminonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C6H8N4/c7-3-5(2-6-1-9-4-10-6)8/h1,4-5H,2H2,(H,9,10)(H2,7,8)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C6H9N3O2", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-(1H-imidazol-4-yl)propanoic acid", "common_name": "histidine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C6H9N3O2/c7-5(6(10)11)1-4-2-8-3-9-4/h2-3,5H,1,7H2,(H,8,9)(H,10,11)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C2H2O2", "iupac_name": "ethanedial", "common_name": "glyoxal", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H2O2/c3-1-2-4/h1-2H", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C3H4N2", "iupac_name": "1H-imidazole", "common_name": "imidazole", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4N2/c1-4-2-5-3-1/h1-3H,(H,4,5)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C4H4N4", "iupac_name": "2,3-diaminobut-2-enedinitrile", "common_name": "diaminomaleonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H4N4/c5-1-3(7)4(8)2-6/h7-8H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C4H3N5", "iupac_name": "5-amino-1H-imidazole-4-carbonitrile", "common_name": "AICN", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H3N5/c5-1-3-4(6)8-2-9-3/h2H,(H3,6,8,9)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "C4H5N3O", "iupac_name": "5-amino-1H-imidazole-4-carboxamide", "common_name": "AICA", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H5N3O/c5-4-2(3(6)8)1-7-4/h1H,(H2,6,8)(H2,5,7)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_018", "formula": "C4H5N3O2", "iupac_name": "5-amino-1H-imidazole-4-carboxylic acid", "common_name": "imidazole-4-carboxylic acid analogue/AICA hydrolysis context", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H5N3O2/c5-4-2(3(8)9)1-6-7-4/h1H,(H,8,9)(H3,5,6,7)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_019", "formula": "C4H4N2O2", "iupac_name": "2-formamido-2-aminoprop-2-enenitrile", "common_name": "N-formyldehydroalanine nitrile", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_020", "formula": "C5H5N3O", "iupac_name": "imidazole derivative from FoDHA-CN cyanide cascade", "common_name": "FoDHA-derived imidazole product", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_021", "formula": "C12H16N6O3", "iupac_name": "2-[(2-amino-3-(1H-imidazol-4-yl)propanoyl)amino]-3-(1H-imidazol-4-yl)propanoic acid", "common_name": "His-His dipeptide", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_003"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "348K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite (Fe3S4), mackinawite (FeS)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent-like conditions; maximum yields near 75C"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-surface mediated reduction of CO2 by H2 on iron-sulfur phases gives reduced one-carbon species represented here as formate.", "reasoning": "Included as the hydrothermal reduced-carbon feeder that links vent chemistry to surface carbonyl chemistry; greigite-catalyzed CO2 reduction at alkaline vent conditions is supported by Lilova et al. (2020), and vent thermodynamic favorability for amino-acid precursor formation is discussed by Kitadai (2015). This is not a histidine-specific demonstrated step and is therefore a network-connecting feeder rather than part of the validated histidine route."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Surface generation/accumulation of formaldehyde from reduced C1 feedstock", "inputs": ["mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-exposed shallow pools; represented as a surface carbonyl accumulation step"}, "mechanism": "Photochemical/oxidation-state reorganization of reduced C1 inventory yields formaldehyde available to surface sugar chemistry.", "reasoning": "The deep report identifies formaldehyde as a highly plausible prebiotic feedstock and essential formose precursor, but does not specify a unique single geochemical route in the histidine literature summary. This step is explicitly speculative but necessary to connect hydrothermal reduced carbon to the literature-established surface formose network for erythrose. Its use is constrained to precursor supply and does not alter the validated Shen et al. (1987, 1990) core histidine route."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Formose entry: formaldehyde dimerization to glycolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_005"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline shallow-pool chemistry; sugar stabilization by borate"}, "mechanism": "Formaldehyde enters formose-type chemistry to generate the C2 aldehyde glycolaldehyde, which then seeds higher sugar formation.", "reasoning": "Formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde are identified in the deep report as highly plausible prebiotic intermediates and glycolaldehyde is a direct precursor to erythrose. Borate stabilization of sugars is supported by Ricardo et al. (2004), and the use of glycolaldehyde as a gateway to erythrose is consistent with the report summary and Yi et al. (2023)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Aldol/formose progression to erythrose", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite), montmorillonite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH 8-9; wet-dry concentration; erythrose is minor and unstable"}, "mechanism": "C2-C1 aldol/formose chemistry generates the C4 aldose erythrose, with borate helping stabilize otherwise labile sugar products.", "reasoning": "Erythrose is the required sugar precursor in the sole demonstrated histidine synthesis. The report states erythrose is a minor unstable formose product (Decker et al., 1982) but can form from glycolaldehyde self-condensation at pH 8-9 (Yi et al., 2023), with borate potentially stabilizing pentose/tetrose-like sugars (Ricardo et al., 2004). This reaction directly supports the Shen et al. (1987, 1990) bottleneck."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "HCN generation and accumulation in surface settings", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 (anatase/rutile), sulfide minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-exposed anoxic pools; represented as feedstock accumulation rather than a single experimentally unique route"}, "mechanism": "Surface photochemical nitrogen-carbon chemistry accumulates hydrogen cyanide, which then serves as the central nitrile feedstock for Strecker and oligomerization reactions.", "reasoning": "The report treats HCN as a central and highly plausible prebiotic feedstock underpinning both formamidine formation and DAMN/AICN chemistry. This step is included as a necessary feeder and is not claimed as a histidine-specific demonstrated transformation. Its role is to supply the literature-established downstream HCN chemistry of Ferris & Orgel (1966), Ferris & Kuder (1970), Shen et al. (1987, 1990), and Green et al. (2023)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Formamidine formation from HCN and ammonia", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite (clay)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "concentrating pools; formamidine is highly labile in water"}, "mechanism": "HCN and ammonia generate amidine functionality represented here as formamidine, the key but prebiotically problematic reagent in the Shen route.", "reasoning": "The deep report explicitly identifies formamidine as deriving from HCN + NH3 but as extremely labile and prebiotically problematic, following the critique of V\u00e1zquez-Salazar et al. (2018). This node is essential because Shen et al. (1987, 1990) require formamidine at 0.3 M for the only successful histidine synthesis."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Shen-Miller-Oro imidazole-4-acetaldehyde formation from erythrose and formamidine", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "298-310K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "none demonstrated in the original work; minerals here act as concentrative/stabilizing agents", "aqueous": "true", "other": "aqueous solution; formamidine about 0.3 M; Schiff base formation followed by Amadori rearrangement; reported 1.6% yield based on erythrose"}, "mechanism": "Erythrose condenses with formamidine to form a Schiff base, then undergoes an Amadori-like rearrangement that constructs the imidazole ring and yields imidazole-4-acetaldehyde.", "reasoning": "This is the critical literature-established bottleneck and the only demonstrated prebiotic route to the direct histidine precursor. The mechanism and yield follow Shen et al. (1987) and Shen et al. (1990). The report emphasizes that this step is chemically remarkable but prebiotically weak because erythrose is minor/unstable and formamidine is hydrolytically labile (V\u00e1zquez-Salazar et al., 2018)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Strecker conversion of imidazole-4-acetaldehyde to histidine aminonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_007", "mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite (clay)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "mildly basic aqueous Strecker conditions"}, "mechanism": "The aldehyde forms an imine with ammonia, cyanide adds to give the alpha-aminonitrile precursor to histidine.", "reasoning": "This is the classical Strecker stage of the Shen-Miller-Or\u00f3 route. The report states that imidazole-4-acetaldehyde reacts with HCN and NH3 to give the alpha-aminonitrile, which on hydrolysis yields histidine; Shen et al. (1990) confirmed the overall sequence by HPLC and MS methods."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Hydrolysis of histidine aminonitrile to histidine", "inputs": ["mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "aqueous hydrolysis during prolonged standing/heating; overall histidine yield reported 3.5% relative to erythrose"}, "mechanism": "Nitrile hydrolysis converts the aminonitrile into the amino acid carboxylate, completing histidine formation.", "reasoning": "This completes the only demonstrated prebiotic histidine synthesis of Shen et al. (1990). Placement in the Biochemical category reflects the network framework's final assembly layer, not a claim of enzymatic requirement. The deep report notes that once imidazole-4-acetaldehyde exists, Strecker elaboration is comparatively straightforward."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Debus-Radziszewski imidazole synthesis", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_004", "mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "298K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "none required in the original mild aqueous reaction; minerals here provide concentration/adsorption", "aqueous": "true", "other": "mild aqueous conditions; room temperature"}, "mechanism": "Glyoxal, formaldehyde, and ammonia condense through diimine-type intermediates to form imidazole.", "reasoning": "Or\u00f3 et al. (1984) demonstrated prebiotic imidazole formation by the Debus-Radziszewski reaction under mild aqueous conditions, and Kua et al. (2011) supported a 1,2-diimine mechanism computationally. The deep report explicitly states this route forms imidazole efficiently but does not provide a demonstrated path onward to histidine."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "HCN tetramerization to diaminomaleonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "surface concentration on sulfide/mineral substrates", "aqueous": "true", "other": "HCN oligomerization in anoxic surface p